Our assignment for this week was to test the following code and determine whether or not corrections needed to be made and if so, what would those be? 

Here is the code provided:

assignment2 <- c(16, 18, 14, 22, 27, 17, 19, 17, 17, 22, 20, 22)



myMean <- function(assignment2) {

  return(sum(assignment) / length(someData))

}



When I run this code in Rstudio is receive the following output:
Error in myMean(assignment2) : object 'assignment' not found

The reason as to why I get this error is because "assignment" has not been created. R can't find assignment because I have not created the conditions in R for it exist. But what does exist is assignment2. It has been given numerical value therefore it now has a specific purpose or value in R.  Let's see what happens when "assignment" is corrected to  "assignment2"

New code: 

assignment2 <- c(16, 18, 14, 22, 27, 17, 19, 17, 17, 22, 20, 22)

myMean <- function(assignment2) {

  return(sum(assignment2) / length(someData))

}

myMean(assignment2)



This is the output we get when we run the code again: 

Error in myMean(assignment2) : object 'someData' not found

The error is encountered again, but this time its for another variable named "someData". And just like "assignment" we have not given any value to a variable named "someData". As a result R does not recognize "someData". As a result when we try to run the function it gives us that error. Let's see what happens with both variable names are corrected. 

New code: 

assignment2 <- c(16, 18, 14, 22, 27, 17, 19, 17, 17, 22, 20, 22)

myMean <- function(assignment2) {

  return(sum(assignment2) / length(assignment2))

}

myMean(assignment2)



Output: 

[1] 19.25



Awesome, after corrected the names of the variables and using a variable that we had already defined we now have a function that properly gives us the mean. 

